    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "Which of the following is an example of misappropriation of assets involving a fixed asset?",
      "tag": "Misappropriation of Fixed Assets",
      "options": [
        "A. Submission of expense report with duplicate receipts",
        "B. Use of company vehicle for personal travel",
        "C. Diversion of checks for vendor payments",
        "D. Creation of phantom employee on payroll"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "The use of a corporate vehicle for personal purposes represents the improper use of company fixed assets for personal benefit — a category of misappropriation of non-monetary assets. (CFE Fraud Examiners Manual 2024)",
      "justification_wrong": "Duplicate expenses are reimbursement fraud; check diversion is alteration; phantom employee is payroll fraud — only personal use of the vehicle constitutes misappropriation of a fixed asset.",
      "difficulty": "EASY",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_006_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "How are asset misappropriation schemes typically concealed in accounting records?",
      "tag": "Concealment of Defalcations",
      "options": [
        "A. Through collusion with external auditors",
        "B. By creating offshore entities to absorb the misappropriated assets",
        "C. Through the use of non-traceable cryptocurrencies",
        "D. By manipulating records to cover the missing asset with false expenses or accounting write-offs"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "When an asset is misappropriated, a fraudulent entry must be created — such as a false expense or accounting write-off — to justify its absence and maintain the accounting equation in balance. (CFE Fraud Examiners Manual)",
      "justification_wrong": "Collusion with auditors, offshore entities, and cryptocurrencies are possible methods but do not describe the fundamental accounting mechanism for concealing asset misappropriation.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_006_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "text": "The CFE exam manual emphasizes that any complex fraud scheme must manipulate which fundamental concept?",
      "tag": "Core Concept",
      "options": [
        "A. The organization's chart of accounts",
        "B. The audit logs and evidence trails",
        "C. The fundamental accounting equation",
        "D. Contracts with related parties"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "The fundamental accounting equation (Assets = Liabilities + Equity) is the backbone of any financial record—all accounting fraud schemes must falsify accounts to maintain balance. (CFE Fraud Examiner Manual)",
      "justification_wrong": "Chart of accounts, audit trails, and related party contracts are important elements but not the fundamental concept that every scheme must manipulate.",
      "difficulty": "EASY",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_006_en.json"
    },
    {
      "question": "Greenfield Manufacturing Inc. is preparing its year-end financial statements for December 31, 2023. The controller has identified several transactions that require proper classification and analysis:\n\n1. On July 1, 2023, the company purchased new production equipment for $480,000 cash. The equipment has an estimated useful life of 8 years with a $48,000 residual value. The company uses straight-line depreciation.\n\n2. During the year, the company incurred $85,000 in costs to repair and maintain existing machinery (normal maintenance). Additionally, $120,000 was spent on a major overhaul of a production line that extended its useful life by 3 years beyond the original estimate.\n\n3. The company's inventory records show the following for Product X:\n   - Beginning inventory: 2,000 units at $50 per unit\n   - Purchases: March 15 - 3,000 units at $52 per unit; September 10 - 4,000 units at $55 per unit\n   - Sales: 6,500 units\n   The company uses a periodic inventory system and is evaluating FIFO vs. weighted average cost methods.\n\n4. On December 1, 2023, Greenfield received a $60,000 advance payment from a customer for products to be delivered in February 2024.\n\nRequired:\na) Calculate the depreciation expense for 2023 related to the new equipment and explain how this affects both the income statement and balance sheet.\n\nb) Explain the appropriate accounting treatment for the $85,000 maintenance costs versus the $120,000 overhaul costs, including the impact on current period financial statements and the rationale under GAAP.\n\nc) Calculate the cost of goods sold and ending inventory value under both FIFO and weighted average cost methods. Explain which method would result in higher net income for 2023 given the price trend, and discuss the impact on financial ratios such as gross profit margin and inventory turnover.\n\nd) Prepare the journal entry to record the advance payment received on December 1, 2023, and explain how this transaction affects the accounting equation and working capital. What would be the impact if this were incorrectly recorded as revenue in 2023?",
      "topic": "S1D01",
      "subtopic": "Accounting Concepts & Financial Analysis",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "num": 4
    },
    {
      "question": "Bright Manufacturing Inc. recently underwent significant restructuring. The company's controller has presented you with the following information for the year ended December 31, 2023:\n\n- The company closed its Eastern Division on September 30, 2023, resulting in a loss on disposal of $850,000 (net of tax of $250,000). The Eastern Division's operating loss from January 1 to September 30, 2023 was $320,000 (net of tax recovery of $95,000).\n\n- In November 2023, management committed to a plan to restructure the Western Division, estimating restructuring costs of $1,200,000. By December 31, 2023, $400,000 had been incurred and paid, with the remainder expected to be paid in Q1 2024.\n\n- The company changed its inventory valuation method from weighted average to FIFO on January 1, 2023. This change increased opening inventory by $275,000 (net of tax of $82,000). Management believes FIFO better reflects current costs.\n\n- A computational error in depreciation expense for 2022 was discovered in March 2023, resulting in an understatement of prior year expenses by $180,000 (net of tax recovery of $54,000).\n\n- Income from continuing operations before these items was $2,500,000 (net of tax of $750,000).\n\nRequired:\nPrepare the statement of comprehensive income for Bright Manufacturing Inc. for the year ended December 31, 2023, starting with income from continuing operations. Show all items in their appropriate classification according to IFRS. Briefly explain your treatment of each item.",
      "answer": "**BRIGHT MANUFACTURING INC.**\n**Statement of Comprehensive Income**\n**For the Year Ended December 31, 2023**\n\nIncome from continuing operations: $2,500,000\n\nDiscontinued operations:\n- Operating loss from Eastern Division: $(320,000)\n- Loss on disposal of Eastern Division: $(850,000)\nLoss from discontinued operations: $(1,170,000)\n\n**Net income: $1,330,000**\n\n**Other comprehensive income: $0**\n\n**Total comprehensive income: $1,330,000**\n\n---\n\n**Explanations:**\n\n1. **Eastern Division closure ($1,170,000 loss)**: Presented as discontinued operations under IFRS 5 because the division represents a separate major line of business that has been disposed of. Both the operating loss during 2023 and the loss on disposal are shown separately from continuing operations.\n\n2. **Western Division restructuring ($400,000 incurred)**: The $400,000 actually incurred is included in income from continuing operations as a period expense. The remaining $800,000 cannot be accrued under IAS 37 unless it meets the criteria for a restructuring provision (detailed plan communicated to affected parties). Restructuring costs are NOT presented separately but remain in continuing operations.\n\n3. **Inventory method change ($275,000)**: Under IFRS (IAS 8), voluntary changes in accounting policy require retrospective application. The $275,000 adjustment should be made to opening retained earnings, NOT shown in the current year's income statement. It represents a prior period adjustment.\n\n4. **Depreciation error ($180,000)**: This is a correction of a prior period error under IAS 8. It should be corrected retrospectively by adjusting opening retained earnings for 2023, NOT included in current year income.\n\n**Note**: The $2,500,000 income from continuing operations is assumed to already reflect the $400,000 restructuring costs actually incurred. If not explicitly stated otherwise, this would need clarification.",
      "num": 5
    },
    {
      "question": "Quantum Industries Inc. is preparing its year-end financial statements for December 31, 2023. The controller has identified several transactions that require proper classification and analysis:\n\n1. A significant customer declared bankruptcy on December 15, 2023, owing $450,000. Quantum had previously assessed this customer as creditworthy with minimal collection risk.\n\n2. The company entered into a 5-year lease agreement on October 1, 2023, for manufacturing equipment with a fair value of $800,000. The lease requires annual payments of $185,000, payable at the beginning of each year. The equipment has an estimated useful life of 8 years with no residual value. Quantum's incremental borrowing rate is 7%, and the lessor's implicit rate is unknown.\n\n3. On July 1, 2023, Quantum sold a division for $5,000,000 cash. The division's net assets had a carrying value of $3,200,000 at the sale date. The division represented a separate major line of business and geographical area of operations.\n\n4. During 2023, Quantum discovered that depreciation expense for equipment purchased in 2021 was understated by $120,000 in both 2021 and 2022 due to an incorrect useful life estimate being applied.\n\n5. Management has decided to change its inventory valuation method from weighted-average cost to FIFO, believing this provides more relevant information. The change will result in inventory being valued $380,000 higher at January 1, 2023.\n\nRequired:\n\nFor EACH of the five items above:\na) Identify the relevant accounting concept(s) or principle(s) that should guide the accounting treatment\nb) Explain how each item should be treated in the 2023 financial statements\nc) Quantify the impact on net income for 2023 where applicable\nd) Discuss any required disclosures\n\nAdditionally:\ne) Analyze how items 1, 3, and 4 would affect Quantum's key financial ratios (current ratio, debt-to-equity, and return on assets), and explain the implications for financial statement users' decision-making.",
      "topic": "S1D01",
      "subtopic": "Accounting Concepts & Financial Analysis",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "num": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "S1D01-Q7",
      "topic": "Revenue Recognition Fraud",
      "description": "A candidate must analyze a company's revenue recognition practices to identify potential fraudulent schemes, assess the impact on financial statements, and recommend appropriate controls and corrective actions.",
      "question": "You are the external auditor for TechFlow Solutions Inc., a software company that went public 18 months ago. During your fieldwork for the year ended December 31, 2023, you discover the following:\n\n1. TechFlow recognizes revenue from multi-year software licenses upfront upon contract signing, even though the software requires significant customization and implementation services over 12-18 months.\n\n2. In Q4 2023, sales representatives were given aggressive targets. You notice:\n   - 15 contracts signed on December 30-31, representing 22% of annual revenue\n   - Several contracts contain unusual side agreements granting customers extended payment terms (up to 24 months) and liberal cancellation rights\n   - Three major customers (representing $4.2M in Q4 revenue) have not yet received the software\n\n3. The CFO has consistently emphasized meeting analyst expectations. The company's stock price is tied to revenue growth targets.\n\n4. Management has been unwilling to provide you with complete documentation for the Q4 contracts, citing \"confidentiality concerns.\"\n\nRequired:\na) Identify and explain the revenue recognition issues and potential fraud indicators present in this scenario.\nb) Analyze the impact on TechFlow's financial statements if revenue has been improperly recognized.\nc) What additional audit procedures would you perform to gather sufficient appropriate evidence?\nd) What are your responsibilities as the auditor if you conclude that material misstatement due to fraud exists?\ne) Recommend internal controls that TechFlow should implement to prevent future revenue recognition issues.",
      "sample_answer": "a) Revenue Recognition Issues and Fraud Indicators:\n\n- Improper revenue recognition timing: Software requiring significant customization should follow ASC 606 guidance treating the contract as containing multiple performance obligations. Revenue should be recognized over time, not upfront.\n\n- Bill-and-hold concerns: Three contracts where software hasn't been delivered should not have revenue recognized.\n\n- Side agreements with extended payment terms and cancellation rights indicate the earnings process is not complete and collectibility is not reasonably assured.\n\n- Channel stuffing: 22% of annual revenue in the last 2 days suggests pressure to meet targets.\n\n- Fraud risk indicators: Management pressure to meet forecasts, stock price implications, aggressive incentives, and management's reluctance to provide documentation.\n\nb) Financial Statement Impact:\n\n- Revenue and accounts receivable are overstated\n- Net income is overstated (assuming software costs already incurred)\n- Deferred revenue is understated\n- Earnings per share is overstated\n- Cash flow from operations may appear weak relative to reported earnings\n- Future periods will show reduced revenue when reversal/correction occurs\n\nc) Additional Audit Procedures:\n\n- Obtain and review all contract documents including side letters\n- Confirm contract terms directly with customers\n- Examine subsequent cash collections and product deliveries\n- Interview sales personnel about year-end pressures\n- Analyze customer acceptance and cancellation history\n- Review board minutes and management communications\n- Test journal entries for unusual revenue recordings\n- Engage forensic specialists if needed\n- Consider engaging legal counsel\n\nd) Auditor Responsibilities:\n\n- Communicate findings to appropriate level of management and those charged with governance (audit committee)\n- Consider implications for auditor's report - likely material misstatement requiring adjustment\n- If management refuses to correct, issue modified opinion (qualified or adverse)\n- Evaluate whether to withdraw from engagement\n- Consider reporting obligations to regulators (SEC) given public company status\n- Document all fraud-related communications and conclusions\n\ne) Recommended Internal Controls:\n\n- Implement formal revenue recognition policy aligned with accounting standards\n- Require legal and finance review/approval of all contracts before revenue recognition\n- Establish centralized contract repository\n- Separate sales compensation from revenue recognition timing\n- Implement contract modification procedures requiring CFO approval\n- Strengthen tone at the top regarding ethical financial reporting\n- Establish whistleblower hotline\n- Provide regular training on revenue recognition standards\n- Implement automated controls in billing systems to flag unusual terms\n- Enhance audit committee oversight of revenue recognition judgments",
      "key_concepts": [
        "Revenue recognition principles (ASC 606)",
        "Fraud risk factors and indicators",
        "Audit procedures for fraud detection",
        "Professional skepticism",
        "Auditor reporting responsibilities",
        "Internal control design",
        "Management override of controls",
        "Performance obligations",
        "Bill-and-hold arrangements"
      ],
      "difficulty": "advanced",
      "time_estimate": 45,
      "cfe_day": 1,
      "num": 7
    },
    {
      "question": "Quantum Technologies Inc. is preparing its year-end financial statements for December 31, 2023. The company's controller has identified several transactions that require proper accounting treatment:\n\n1. On October 1, 2023, Quantum received $120,000 from a customer for a 24-month service contract starting on that date.\n\n2. The company purchased equipment on January 1, 2021, for $500,000 with an estimated useful life of 10 years and no residual value. On January 1, 2023, management determined that the remaining useful life should be 5 years from that date due to technological changes.\n\n3. Quantum holds a patent acquired on July 1, 2020, for $300,000 with a legal life of 20 years. However, due to rapid industry innovation, the economic useful life is estimated at 10 years.\n\n4. During 2023, the company incurred $80,000 in research costs and $45,000 in development costs for a new product. The development costs were incurred after technological feasibility was established on September 1, 2023.\n\n5. Quantum's inventory records show the following for Product X: Beginning inventory of 1,000 units at $50/unit; purchased 3,000 units at $55/unit; purchased 2,000 units at $60/unit; sold 4,500 units. The company uses the weighted average cost method.\n\nRequired:\nA) Calculate the revenue that should be recognized for the service contract in 2023.\n\nB) Determine the depreciation expense for the equipment for the year ended December 31, 2023, and explain the accounting principle applied.\n\nC) Calculate the amortization expense for the patent for the year ended December 31, 2023.\n\nD) Explain the proper accounting treatment for the research and development costs and calculate the amount that should be expensed in 2023.\n\nE) Calculate the cost of goods sold and ending inventory value for Product X.\n\nF) Discuss which fundamental accounting concepts or principles are most relevant to transactions 1, 2, and 4.",
      "answer": "A) Revenue Recognition for Service Contract:\n- Contract period: 24 months starting October 1, 2023\n- Contract value: $120,000\n- Monthly revenue: $120,000 ÷ 24 = $5,000\n- Months in 2023: October, November, December = 3 months\n- Revenue recognized in 2023: $5,000 × 3 = $15,000\n- Deferred revenue at December 31, 2023: $120,000 - $15,000 = $105,000\n\nB) Depreciation Expense for Equipment:\n- Original cost: $500,000\n- Annual depreciation (2021-2022): $500,000 ÷ 10 = $50,000\n- Accumulated depreciation at December 31, 2022: $50,000 × 2 = $100,000\n- Carrying amount at January 1, 2023: $500,000 - $100,000 = $400,000\n- Revised remaining useful life: 5 years\n- Depreciation expense for 2023: $400,000 ÷ 5 = $80,000\n\nAccounting Principle Applied: Change in accounting estimate. The change in useful life is accounted for prospectively, not retrospectively. The remaining carrying amount is depreciated over the revised remaining useful life.\n\nC) Amortization Expense for Patent:\n- Cost: $300,000\n- Amortization period: Shorter of legal life (20 years) or economic life (10 years) = 10 years\n- Annual amortization: $300,000 ÷ 10 = $30,000\n- Amortization expense for 2023: $30,000\n\nD) Research and Development Costs:\nUnder ASPE or traditional GAAP treatment:\n- Research costs: Always expensed as incurred = $80,000\n- Development costs: Under ASPE, can be capitalized if certain criteria are met (including technological feasibility). Since technological feasibility was established September 1, 2023:\n  - If criteria are met: Capitalize $45,000 and amortize over useful life\n  - If criteria are not met: Expense $45,000\n\nUnder IFRS (IAS 38):\n- Research costs: Expensed = $80,000\n- Development costs: Can be capitalized if six criteria are met (including technical feasibility)\n  - Capitalize $45,000 if criteria met\n\nAssuming criteria are not fully met or using conservative approach:\n- Total R&D expense in 2023: $80,000 + $45,000 = $125,000\n\nIf development costs are capitalized:\n- Expense in 2023: $80,000 (research only)\n- Capitalized: $45,000 (development)\n\nE) Cost of Goods Sold and Ending Inventory (Weighted Average):\n- Beginning inventory: 1,000 units × $50 = $50,000\n- Purchase 1: 3,000 units × $55 = $165,000\n- Purchase 2: 2,000 units × $60 = $120,000\n- Total available: 6,000 units costing $335,000\n- Weighted average cost per unit: $335,000 ÷ 6,000 = $55.83 (rounded)\n\n- Units sold: 4,500\n- COGS: 4,500 × $55.83 = $251,235\n\n- Ending inventory: 1,500 units × $55.83 = $83,745\n- Verification: $335,000 - $251,235 = $83,765 (slight difference due to rounding)\n\nF) Fundamental Accounting Concepts/Principles:\n\nTransaction 1 (Service Contract):\n- Revenue Recognition Principle: Revenue is recognized when earned (as services are provided), not when cash is received\n- Matching Principle: Revenue should be matched to the period in which services are delivered\n- Accrual Basis Accounting: Transactions are recorded when they occur, not when cash changes hands\n\nTransaction 2 (Equipment Depreciation):\n- Matching Principle: The cost of the asset is matched to the periods that benefit from its use\n- Going Concern: Assumes the business will continue operating, justifying systematic allocation over useful life\n- Change in Accounting Estimate: Changes are applied prospectively, not retrospectively\n- Consistency vs. Comparability: While the method remains consistent (straight-line), the estimate changes based on new information\n\nTransaction 4 (R&D Costs):\n- Matching Principle: Costs should be matched to future benefits\n- Conservatism (Prudence): When outcome is uncertain, recognize expenses rather than assets\n- Asset Recognition Criteria: An item should only be recognized as an asset if future economic benefits are probable and the cost can be measured reliably\n- Substance Over Form: The economic reality of uncertain future benefits typically results in expensing R&D despite cash outflows for potential future benefits",
      "num": 8
    }
  ]
}